NYC sure knows how to do pizza!  This joint is a fast casual Italian cafe. Offering hot pasta, salads, some sandwiches, but most of all - serving up quality pizza.  We walked in for lunch, after having window shopped the other area spots. This place looked best to serve up the New York taste without the New York price.  The place is well lit, with booth style seating on the right when you walk in, and more tables towards the back, once the ordering bar on the left stops. We ended up getting slices to dine in and we thoroughly enjoyed the offerings. The staff warmed up the slice juusssttt right, and we had options for toppings to add on our own. These are big New York slices, so one was more than enough for each of us. Everything was quickly taken care of and the staff was very friendly, chatting us up on what they recommend from the different pizza options.  I also noticed that the place delivers with their own branded bikes parked outside. This is an added plus - making this place an option for those cold nights that won't get you outside.  Great find and overall enjoyable experience!

Disclaimer: Ive been eating here for ten years. Literally. The pizza and salads are okay- there are definitely better choices in the neighborhood- but the pasta bar has kept me coming back. You select your pasta, sauce and protein/vegetable add ons and the cook prepares it right in front of you, behind a glass of course. It's nothing fancy, nor is it overly delicious, but for less than 10 bucks you can get a solid pasta dish customized how you like it. You can't beat that for a weekday lunch. No, I probably wouldn't go for dinner but definitely for lunch, multiple times a week. My go to pasta is the creamy pesto with grilled chicken. Feel free to tell the cook to go easy or heavy on the pesto or cream sauce. Another favorite is the pasta in marinara with roasted vegetables. The taste is very earthy and garlic-y, but good, if you're into that sort of thing.  This is definitely not a destination restaurant. I only ever go if when I am in the neighborhood for school (back in the day), work (currently) or some other random reason that brings me to Montague street.
